        <body>
            <div type="month" mhs:startingPage="286"  mhs:precedingFile="" mhs:followingFile="JQADiaries-v24-1800-02-p288.xml" mhs:volume="24">
                <bibl n="metadata"><date from="1800-01-01" to="1800-01-31"/></bibl>

                <!-- D/JQA/24.1958 -->
                <!-- ask Bill: is there an issue that 1 Feb. 1800 entry is at the bottom of this file? How to handle? -->

                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-01">
                    <head>1 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-01"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <pb n="286"/>
                        <dateline><hi rend="italic">January 1800.</hi></dateline>
                        <p><date>1. </date>The weather has a good deal moderated— Sent and received
                            visiting cards as usual on New-Year’s day. Spent the Evening at <persRef
                                ref="engstrom-lars">M. d’Engeström’s</persRef>, in a large company.
                            I did not stay to supper— Played whist with <persRef ref="u">Countess
                                Moltke</persRef>, her sister, <persRef ref="u">Madame de
                                Prittwitz</persRef>, and <persRef ref="u">Madame de
                                Zastrow</persRef>— The <persRef
                                ref="brown-isabella;brown-fanny;brown-margaret">Miss
                                Brown’s</persRef> spent a couple of hours with <persRef
                                key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                Adams</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-02">
                    <head>2 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-02"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                        <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>2. </date><persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> was bled this morning, and bore the
                            operation well, but fainted in the Evening just before going to bed—
                            Went to the play, and saw <persRef ref="lessing-gotthold"
                                >Lessing’s</persRef> Minna von Barnhelm— Like his Emilia Galotti, it
                            seems to me better for reading than upon the stage, where it is cold—
                            The weather was extremely so this evening, and the <hi
                                rend="strikethrough">season</hi> performance appeared to partake of
                            the season— Found <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
                                Brown</persRef>, when I came home. The translation of Oberon
                            flags—at least as to the success of the work.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-03">
                    <head>3 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-03"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>3. </date>Have a bad cold myself, and <persRef
                                key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                Adams</persRef> continues very weak and unwell— Stormy weather— I
                            did not go out of the house the whole day. <persRef
                                ref="vonfinckenstein-karl">Count Finckenstein</persRef>, the eldest
                            Minister in the department of foreign affairs, which post he has held
                            more than fifty years, died very suddenly this day at about noon— He had
                            been employed in the diplomatic career under <persRef
                                ref="frederick-william-i">Frederic William the
                            first</persRef>—Father of the Great <persRef ref="frederick-ii"
                                >Frederic</persRef>; and was probably the oldest Minister of State
                            in Europe— He was eighty-five years old— He transacted business this
                            morning and signed the dispatches to be sent to the Ministers in foreign
                            Courts, by to-morrow’s post.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-04">
                    <head>4 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-04"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>4. </date><persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> A.</persRef> very unwell again—all the forenoon, but
                            rather better the remainder of the day— <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >r:</hi> Knoblauch</persRef> called on me before dinner, and the
                                <persRef ref="danadia-joao">Vicomte d’Anadia</persRef> in the
                            Evening, relating to some token of respect from the corps diplomatique
                            to the memory of the late <persRef ref="vonfinckenstein-karl">Count
                                Fink</persRef>.— He is to consult with <persRef
                                ref="alvensleben-philipp">Baron Alvensleben</persRef> about it. Had
                            a lesson of German this morning— The Oberon grows very tedious.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-05">
                    <head>5 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-05"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                        <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>5. </date>Began to read this morning a sermon of <persRef
                                ref="tillotson-john">Tillotson</persRef>, but was obliged soon
                            obliged to desist; owing to a severe cold which permits me not to read
                            loud— <persRef ref="vonbruhl-sophia">Countess Brühl’s</persRef>
                            <persRef ref="bruhl-maria;vonbruhl-fanny">daughters</persRef> pass’d the
                            Evening with <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> A.</persRef>— Went to Court, and stayed untill supper
                            time; nine O’clock.— Played whist, with <persRef ref="u">Madame de
                                Bredow</persRef>, M<hi rend="superscript">lle.</hi> de<space/>and an Officer.—
                            Made my Compliments to <persRef ref="alvensleben-philipp">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">r:</hi> Alvensleben</persRef>, who is made a Count,
                            with an additional salary, upon the decease of <persRef
                                ref="vonfinckenstein-karl">Count Finckenstein</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-06">
                    <head>6 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-06"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>6. </date><persRef ref="vonbruhl-sophia">Countess Brühl</persRef>,
                            spent the greatest part of the Evening with <persRef
                                key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                Adams</persRef>.— The weather grew again very cold; and was at the
                            latter part of the Evening at 10 degrees of <persRef ref="reaumur-rene"
                                >Reaumur</persRef> below 0.— Wrote part of a letter, this forenoon
                            to <persRef ref="murray-william2">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
                                Murray</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-07">
                    <head>7 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-07"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>7. </date>Called at <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
                                Schickler’s</persRef> counting-house.— Did not otherwise go out,
                            through the day— Miss Brown spent the Evening with <persRef
                                key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                Adams</persRef>— Read to her, the remnant of the first book, the
                            whole of the second, and the part of the third which I have done, of the
                            translation of Oberon.—</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-08">
                    <head>8 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-08"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>8— </date><persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> taken ill this morning, in the process
                            of a fourth misfortune, like three others which she has gone through
                            since we arrived at Berlin— She remained all day in bed, suffering no
                            pain; and still entertaining some hopes— Evening party at <persRef
                                ref="u">Count Podewils’s</persRef>— I was there about half an
                            hour—</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-09">
                    <head>9 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-09"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>9. </date>After an uneasy, restless and in some degree painful
                            night, <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                A</persRef>— has this day gone through, as I hope, the worst of her
                            misfortune— She was for about three hours excessively ill— I can only
                            pray to God, that there may never again be the possibility of another
                            like event— A better hope, it were folly to indulge; for in cases like
                            this hope itself is but an aggravation of misery— I did not leave the
                            house, the whole day— But at night was so overcome with fatigue and
                            anxiety, that at 8 o’clock I retired to bed.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-10">
                    <head>10 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-10"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>10. </date><persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> is easier though yet extremely weak—
                            Dined at <persRef ref="bunau-gunther">Count Bunau’s</persRef>, with a
                            small party. We were to have been thirteen at table; but <persRef
                                ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> de Sellentin</persRef>, one of the
                            guests making it a point never to sit down in that number the <persRef
                                ref="vonbunau-erdmuthe">Countess</persRef> upon being informed of
                            his scruples, called in one of her young daughters, and made her dine
                            with us. Came home immediately after dinner, and spent the evening at my
                            wife’s bed side.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-11">
                    <head>11 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-11"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>11. </date>Wrote to <persRef ref="murray-william2">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >r:</hi> Murray</persRef> and <persRef ref="pitcairn-joseph"
                                    >M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Pitcairn</persRef>; begin to attend
                            again to my translation, which has for two days been almost wholly
                            suspended— Walk’d again this day— <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine"
                                    >M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— did not yet quit her
                            bed.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-12">
                    <head>12 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-12"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>12. </date>The weather begins to moderate, after a full month of
                            rigorous cold weather— The thermometer for the first time during that
                            period was above the freezing point in the sun; and only two or three
                            degrees below it in the shade— <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine"
                                    >M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— was up for a few hours
                            this afternoon.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-13">
                    <head>13 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-13"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <pb n="287" type="ms"/>
                        <p><date>13. </date><persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> very ill all day with a severe
                            head-ache— The weather continues now to be very moderate. Miss Brown was
                            here about an hour in the Evening.— Wrote a short Letter to the <persRef
                                ref="pickering-timothy">Secretary of State</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-14">
                    <head>14 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-14"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>14. </date>Finished the third book, and began the fourth of
                            Oberon.— Lesson from <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
                                Catel</persRef> this morning.— Letter to <persRef
                                ref="murray-william2">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Murray</persRef>.—
                                <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                A</persRef>— somewhat better than she has yet been since her
                            illness— Read to her this Evening the Officer’s tale, in the new
                            Canterbury tales by the <persRef ref="lee-harriet;lee-sophia">Miss
                                Lee’s</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-15">
                    <head>15 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-15"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>15. </date><persRef ref="ofarrillyherrera-gonzalo">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >r:</hi> O’Farril</persRef> called this afternoon to pay me a
                            visit.— Read in the evening to <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine"
                                    >M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef> part of the Clergyman’s
                            tale by <persRef ref="lee-sophia">Miss Lee</persRef>— Did more than
                            usual of the Oberon.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-16">
                    <head>16 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-16"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>16. </date>Lesson of German.— Went in the afternoon to pay the
                            visits with <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Boissier</persRef>,
                            at the Courts, but, were no where received.— Was at the <persRef
                                ref="engstrom-lars">Swedish Minister’s</persRef>, where the <persRef
                                    ref="sofia">Princess of Sweden</persRef>, who has just arrived here,
                            pass’d the Evening.— Stay’d there about an hour, and then went to the
                                <persRef ref="u">Baron de Hagen’s</persRef>— Came home before nine.
                            The two eldest Miss Brown’s had past the Evening with <persRef
                                key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                Adams</persRef>, who suffered almost all day, very much with a pain
                            in her arm, where she was bled.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-17">
                    <head>17 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-17"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>17. </date>Moderate and thawing weather— Walking before dinner, met
                                <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                                Garlike</persRef>— <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> yet extremely weak, and
                            quite unwell.— Read to her this evening the remainder of the clergyman’s
                            tale by <persRef ref="lee-sophia">Miss Lee</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-18">
                    <head>18 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-18"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>18. </date>Lesson with <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
                                Catel</persRef>— Dined with the English prince <persRef
                                ref="augustusfrederick">Augustus</persRef>; being the celebration of
                            the <persRef ref="charlotte2">Queen of England’s</persRef> birth day.—
                            The company consisted of the English and Hanoverians now here; with
                                <persRef ref="deluc-jean">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> De Luc</persRef>,
                            and <persRef ref="demeuron-charles">General Meuron</persRef>— But was
                            not so numerous as last year— Nor kept up to so late an hour— It was
                            however past seven o’clock when I came home— Weather moderate, and
                            rainy.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-19">
                    <head>19 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-19"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                        <subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>19. </date><persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs.</hi> Adams</persRef> took a ride out for the first time
                            since her illness, but had not strength enough to support the effort—
                                <persRef ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown</persRef>
                            spent the greatest part of the Evening.— Was at Court at the Palace: the
                            first that has yet been held this year— The carnaval having been
                            suspended for a fortnight by the <persRef ref="louiseauguste"
                                >Queen’s</persRef> illness— Presented <persRef ref="u">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">r:</hi> Boissier</persRef>— Play’d whist with him,
                            and <persRef ref="u">Count Moltke</persRef>, and <persRef ref="u">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">r:</hi> Knoblauch</persRef>— Saw <persRef
                                ref="bylandt-willem">Count Byland</persRef> there who told me he
                            came from England in the packet with Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                            <persRef ref="ellsworth-oliver">Ellsworth</persRef> and <persRef
                                ref="davie-william">Davie</persRef>. He was mistaken.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-20">
                    <head>20 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-20"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>20. </date><persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> A</persRef>— somewhat better; so that she spent part
                            of the Evening at <persRef ref="brown-charles">Doctor Brown’s</persRef>—
                            Went to see the first Opera, Semiramide.— The Music by <persRef
                                ref="himmel-friedrich">Himmel</persRef>— It was hiss’d off the stage
                            at Naples; and is indeed very indifferent music— <persRef
                                ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef>
                            called upon us after the Opera; and spent an hour with us.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-21">
                    <head>21 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-21"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>21. </date>This evening was the first redoute, but I did not go.—
                            Took a short walk before dinner; and met the <persRef ref="u">chevalier
                                d’Aguilar</persRef>.— The translation from Oberon now engrosses
                            almost all the leisure time I have— I did this day nothing else; and the
                            practice of writing as yet seems to give no more facility than I had at
                            first—</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-22">
                    <head>22 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-22"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>22— </date>Beautiful weather; but somewhat cooler than for a few
                            days past— <persRef ref="u">Madame de Sartoris</persRef> called in the
                            afternoon and spent an hour with <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine"
                                    >M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Adams</persRef>, who continues very
                            unwell, and excessively weak— I now read nothing.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-23">
                    <head>23 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-23"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>23— </date>The <persRef ref="frederica-louise2"
                                >queen-mother</persRef> was to have held a court this evening, but
                            she is unwell and it was postponed— Met <persRef ref="u">M.
                                d’Aguilar</persRef> walking under the trees— <persRef
                                key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                Adams</persRef> went to spend the Evening at <persRef
                                ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>; but was
                            so unwell that she was obliged very early to come home; and was
                            afterwards very ill.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-24">
                    <head>24 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-24"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                        <subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>24. </date>I passed a sleepless night.— These violent, long
                            continued and frequently repeated shocks from the state of <persRef
                                key="adams-louisa-catherine">my wife’s</persRef> health must at last
                            have an effect upon mine.— Walking this day before dinner I met <persRef
                                ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Arbuthnot</persRef>,
                            who walk’d with me— He was at the <persRef ref="frederica-louise2">Queen
                                mother’s</persRef> last evening, where instead of her Court, she had
                            a play, and perform’d a part herself.— Read in the Evening a canto of
                            the Fairy Queen.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-25">
                    <head>25 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-25"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>25. </date>Had a second totally sleepless night.— I got up and read
                            for two or three hours, to see if that would more compose me but did not
                            succeed— Consulted at length <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi
                                    rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown</persRef> who prescribed a draught for
                            me— Walk’d with <persRef ref="u">M. d’Aguilar</persRef>.— I have no
                            pain, but only an extreme agitation of the nerves, which deprives me of
                            sleep— Did not go this evening to the assembly at <persRef
                                ref="vonmollendorf-richard">Marshall Möllendorf’s</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-26">
                    <head>26 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-26"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                        <subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
                        <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>26. </date>Third, wholly sleepless night.— Though the effects of
                            the draught very much composed my nerves, and I was much easier than the
                            former nights— Took a long walk; meet <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin"
                                    >M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef> who walk’d with me.
                            We <pb n="288" type="ms"/>We were caught in the rain— I called at the
                            Ville de Paris to visit <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
                                Ellison</persRef>, but he was not at home. <persRef ref="u">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">r:</hi> Allingham</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">r:</hi> Baudelaire</persRef> called upon me— In the
                            evening I went to the <persRef ref="louiseauguste">Queen’s</persRef>
                            court, and ball— Introduced to <persRef ref="beurnonville-pierre"
                                >General Beurnonville</persRef> the new french Minister— Play’d
                            whist with <persRef ref="u">Countess Moltke</persRef>
                            <persRef ref="bylandt-willem">Count Byland</persRef>, and <persRef
                                ref="alvensleben-ludwig">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Alvensleben</persRef> the Officer—
                            Came home before ten—</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-27">
                    <head>27 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-27"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>27. </date>At length with the help of an opiate draught I had some
                            sleep— Feel something heavy the greater part of this day— Was at the
                            Opera this evening.— Finish’d the fourth book of Oberon.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-28">
                    <head>28 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-28"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>28. </date><persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
                                Baudelaire</persRef> called upon me for a Passport, but he does not
                            appear to be an American Citizen, and I could give him none. Pass’d the
                            Evening at the Minister <persRef ref="alvensleben-philipp"
                                >Alvensleben’s</persRef>; previous to the Redoute— I came home
                            before supper.— <persRef ref="brown-isabella">Miss B. Brown</persRef>,
                            with <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                Adams</persRef>— Began the 5<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi> book of
                            Oberon.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-29">
                    <head>29 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-29"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>29. </date>Weather moderate but part of the day rainy— Walk’d an
                            hour under the trees— Met <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef>— Read in the Evening a
                            Canto from the Fairy Queen— Not being altogether well, could read no
                            more.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-30">
                    <head>30 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-30"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
                        <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>30. </date>Fine weather— Met <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef> walking under the trees,
                            and walk’d with him— Ball at the <persRef ref="frederica-louise2">Queen
                                Mother’s</persRef>— Play’d Whist with the Ministers <persRef
                                ref="vonheinitz-friedrich">Heinitz</persRef> and <persRef ref="u"
                                >Buchholtz</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
                                Knoblauch</persRef>— Came home before supper— <persRef
                                key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                Adams</persRef> spent the Evening at <persRef ref="brown-mary">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-31">
                    <head>31 January 1800</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01-31"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>31. </date><persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
                                Ellison</persRef> of New-York called upon me this forenoon.— My
                            translation again grows very tedious; and more difficult than ever—
                            Instead of going to the Opera, staid at home and read a Canto in the
                            Fairy Queen, the last of the first book; and likewise a book of the
                            Iliad.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
              
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-01-xx">
                    <head>Day</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-01"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date><hi rend="italic">Day</hi>.</date> As the last month, excepting
                            inasmuch as the course has been interrupted by my wife’s illness.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
